Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["11. Summary", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"2af51462-9f5f-4830-b120-dac608841305"],

Cell["\<\
1. Elastic Mie scattering coefficients a_n, b_n, c_n are computed by solving \
4\[Times]4 (P-SV) and 2\[Times]2 (SH) boundary condition systems.

2. Effective material contrasts are extracted via direct Legendre projection:
     n=0 (monopole)   \[Rule] bulk modulus contrast  \[CapitalDelta]\[Kappa]*
     n=1 (dipole)     \[Rule] density contrast       \[CapitalDelta]\[Rho]*
     n=2 (quadrupole) \[Rule] shear modulus contrast  \[CapitalDelta]\[Mu]*

3. The Eshelby-corrected Rayleigh T-matrix uses the exact result:
     A = \[Minus](9\[Minus]10\[Nu])/(30\[Mu](1\[Minus]\[Nu]))
     B = 1/(30\[Mu](1\[Minus]\[Nu]))
   from the distributional \[Delta]-function in \[Integral] G_{ij,kl} \
d\\[ThreeSuperior]x.

4. Mie-extracted contrasts match Eshelby-corrected Rayleigh to machine \
precision at ALL contrast levels (0.01% to 50%), validating that:
   \[Bullet] The Eshelby \[Delta]-function is exact (not approximate)
   \[Bullet] The self-consistent amplification factors are correct
   \[Bullet] The Legendre projection extraction is contamination-free

5. At finite ka, the Mie and Rayleigh results diverge as expected, since the \
Rayleigh formula only captures the leading ka\\[ThreeSuperior] order.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b39b4e99-65d9-443c-b8c7-bbb8e36eec51"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
